    <h1>Abstraction in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p><strong>Abstraction</strong> allows you to hide the complex implementation details and expose only the essential functionality. In C#, this is achieved using <strong>abstract classes</strong> and <strong>interfaces</strong>.</p>

    <h2>Example 1: Abstract Class</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Using Abstract Classes</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public abstract class Shape
{
    public abstract void Draw(); // Abstract method has no body
}

public class Circle : Shape
{
    public override void Draw()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Drawing a Circle");
    }
}

public class Rectangle : Shape
{
    public override void Draw()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Drawing a Rectangle");
    }
}

// Usage
Shape s1 = new Circle();
Shape s2 = new Rectangle();
s1.Draw(); // Output: Drawing a Circle
s2.Draw(); // Output: Drawing a Rectangle
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Points About Abstraction</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Abstract classes cannot be instantiated directly.</li>
        <li>Derived classes must implement abstract methods.</li>
        <li>Abstraction hides unnecessary details and shows only the relevant data and behavior.</li>
        <li>Helps to reduce complexity and increase code maintainability.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercise</h2>
    <p>Create an abstract class <code>Vehicle</code> with an abstract method <code>StartEngine()</code>. Then create two derived classes <code>Car</code> and <code>Motorcycle</code> that implement the <code>StartEngine()</code> method with appropriate messages. Test your objects by calling <code>StartEngine()</code>.</p>

